was also brought a lot

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:49.640
of changes to the cuisine.

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:52.790
Turks it started to populate
the territory of Azerbaijan

00:27:52.790 --> 00:27:54.300
from the 6th to the 11th century.

00:27:54.300 --> 00:27:57.580
More Turks came in the 11th
century, and with them,

00:27:57.580 --> 00:28:01.840
they brought their own cooking
techniques, their own ingredients.

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:06.600
They brought this art of making
kebabs, very down to earth dish,

00:28:06.600 --> 00:28:09.720
but it was very popular
in Azerbaijan.

00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:14.450
They also brought dumplings, which
are believed to have traveled

00:28:14.450 --> 00:28:19.370
through Central Asia from China,
and we have a lot of dumplings.

00:28:19.370 --> 00:28:21.950
You can see the picture
in the middle.

00:28:21.950 --> 00:28:25.450
These dumplings are called guza

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:28.170
and they resemble Chinese
[non-English word spoken]

00:28:28.170 --> 00:28:29.470
or Japanese[non-English
word spoken].

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:30.770
And Azerbaijan gurza.

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:33.320
I think the name is
very similar, although,

00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:35.010
guza also is the name of a snake.

00:28:35.010 --> 00:28:39.680
So also, you see arishta, which
is believed to have traveled

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:43.060
from Persia, although it's believed

00:28:43.060 --> 00:28:46.790
that the Turks really embraced
it and made it their own.

00:28:46.790 --> 00:28:48.330
We use noodles.

00:28:48.330 --> 00:28:49.720
Those are noodles, basically.

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:53.810
And there is also, we were also
introduced to the use of yogurt,

00:28:53.810 --> 00:28:56.090
which is a staple in
Azerbaijani cuisine.

00:28:56.090 --> 00:28:58.670
We scoop yogurt on
top of many dishes,

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:00.600
vegetarian dishes, pasta dishes.

00:29:00.600 --> 00:29:03.590
You can see in the picture
soup that's called dovgha.

00:29:03.590 --> 00:29:06.250
It's a yogurt soup filled
with lots of fresh herbs.

00:29:06.250 --> 00:29:10.450
It's very refreshing and
delicious at the same time.

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:12.540
The most dramatic impact of --

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:16.110
on Azerbaijani cuisine happen
during the Soviet Union.

00:29:16.110 --> 00:29:18.960
What happened during the
Soviet Union, you know,

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:22.030
the Soviets had this
idea of the same for all.

00:29:22.030 --> 00:29:27.190 position:56%
So that means that all the republics
that were in the Soviet Union,

00:29:27.190 --> 00:29:30.090
part of the Soviet Union,
15 republics altogether,

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:34.240
they had to have the same
eating habits, the same menus,

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:37.620
so they introduced the
same for all style.

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:40.280
Cafeterias opened across
the country,

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:43.190
and all of these cafeterias
served the Soviet-style foods,

00:29:43.190 --> 00:29:44.580
which include some
of the things you see

00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:46.640
in the picture [non-English
word spoken], for example.

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:48.690
These sausages, Soviet-style
sausages.

00:29:48.690 --> 00:29:50.100
There was mashed potatoes;

00:29:50.100 --> 00:29:53.190
[non-English word spoken],
which is meat patties.

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:58.270
Buckwheat and other
similar Russian foods.

00:29:58.270 --> 00:30:01.040
So everything was controlled
from Moscow.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:03.930
That's where all the rules were
made, all the decrees were adopted.

00:30:03.930 --> 00:30:08.570
And the cuisine was primarily based
on elements of Russian cuisine,

00:30:08.570 --> 00:30:14.840 position:56%
although for festive occasions, they
adopted elements of other cuisines.

00:30:14.840 --> 00:30:16.140
For example [non-English
word spoken],

00:30:16.140 --> 00:30:17.440
which comes from the word
[non-English word spoken].

00:30:17.440 --> 00:30:18.740
It's a kebab.

00:30:18.740 --> 00:30:22.220
They adopted it from the Caucuses
and also from Central Asia,

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:26.100
but mostly it was built on the
elements of Russian cuisine.

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:34.440
Some not very good things
happened during the Soviet time.

00:30:34.440 --> 00:30:35.840
Rice production declined.

00:30:35.840 --> 00:30:40.500 position:56%
When I was researching for my book,
I realized that before the Russians,

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:42.820
before the Soviet Union was
established in Azerbaijan,

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:46.590
there was a big rice-growing
industry in the country.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:48.800
When the Russians came,
when the Soviets came,

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:53.610
they realized that this is a very
labor's process to grow rice,

00:30:53.610 --> 00:30:56.450
and it wasn't really fitting
the Soviet style of eating.

00:30:56.450 --> 00:31:00.060
So a lot of plantations, rice
plantations, were abolished,

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:03.420
and instead of them, cabbage
plantations were started,

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:06.200
potato plantations started.

00:31:06.200 --> 00:31:08.870
So rice dishes that
were very popular before

00:31:08.870 --> 00:31:16.310
and were really a part of the
cuisine before, now they became,

00:31:16.310 --> 00:31:19.030
they started to be served
at the end of the dinner

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:21.770 position:56%
for something, or something festive.

00:31:21.770 --> 00:31:24.630
Spice bazaars also were demolished,

00:31:24.630 --> 00:31:28.630
because Soviet cuisine did not
require the use of a lot of spices.

00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:31.450
So spice bazaars disappeared,
as well.

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:36.170
And new drinks came into existence,
such as European-style drinks.

00:31:36.170 --> 00:31:41.330
Sharbats disappeared, and the
German winemaking tradition

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:45.550
that existed before the Soviets
came also suffered, as well.

00:31:45.550 --> 00:31:51.100
We had a German population
Azerbaijan that came.

00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:55.440 position:56%
Those were German colonies that were
established in the 19th century,

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:57.780
and they brought with them
their winemaking skills,

00:31:57.780 --> 00:32:00.730
and they started winemaking
industry in Azerbaijan.

00:32:00.730 --> 00:32:04.000
Unfortunately, they had to be
exiled to Siberia and Kazakhstan

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.180
because of the war of
the USSR and Germany.

00:32:06.180 --> 00:32:09.150
In 1941, they had to
leave Azerbaijan,

00:32:09.150 --> 00:32:14.020
and these are some pictures
of the German winemaking time,

00:32:14.020 --> 00:32:16.350
and new breads were introduced.

00:32:16.350 --> 00:32:19.620
Instead of traditional breads, such
as lavash, tandoor, and others,

00:32:19.620 --> 00:32:23.390 position:56%
Soviet style loaves, long and round,
were established across the country,

00:32:23.390 --> 00:32:26.180
and my grandfather actually
owned one Soviet bakery.

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:27.480
That's his picture.

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:28.880
This is a picture of him.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:33.070
He ran away from the
Stalinist exile.

00:32:33.070 --> 00:32:36.880
He hid in another region, and later
on, he realized there was a need

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:39.660
for a Soviet-style
bakery, and he started one.

00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:41.320
So that's him down there.

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:45.490
And after the collapse
of the Soviet Union,

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:46.800
goods things started to happen.

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:49.890
We started to receive a lot of
new foods from other countries.

00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:53.020
The first foods that came to us
in Azerbaijan were Turkish foods,

00:32:53.020 --> 00:32:55.510
because of the proximity
of the regions,

00:32:55.510 --> 00:32:57.500
and also because of the
tastes were very similar.

00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.740
So the first foods that came
to Azerbaijan, I remember,

00:33:00.740 --> 00:33:05.060
in the early 1990s, when the
Soviet Union had just collapsed,

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:07.940
was the doughnut kebab,
the spiraling meat

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:12.050
that was really fancy back then,
but it's really widely spread now.

00:33:12.050 --> 00:33:15.090
So Azerbaijanis started to
reclaim their traditions

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:19.390
of preparing traditional meals
more often now in restaurants,

00:33:19.390 --> 00:33:22.470
they serve a lot of things
that were not served before,

00:33:22.470 --> 00:33:23.950
for example, piti.

00:33:23.950 --> 00:33:25.250
This is piti.

00:33:25.250 --> 00:33:28.840
It's a lamb stew with chestnuts
cooked in a special pot.

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.620 position:56%
And special days in food traditions,

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:33.440
you've heard about
Nowruz a little bit.

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:41.430
So I just want to say that a lot
of traditions, a lot of holidays,

00:33:41.430 --> 00:33:43.860
they have food traditions
involved in them.

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:49.280
So in weddings, a lot of foods,
even when two families meet,

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:52.300 position:56%
the families of the bride and groom,
the first ceremony, when they agreed

00:33:52.300 --> 00:33:53.840
to the marriage, is a tea ceremony.

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:58.350
They sweeten the tea, which
means that the union is going

00:33:58.350 --> 00:34:02.360
to take place, and so the
commemorations, for example,

00:34:02.360 --> 00:34:04.500
when death happens in the
family, halwa is made.

00:34:04.500 --> 00:34:07.690
It's believed to soothe
the pain of the grief,

00:34:07.690 --> 00:34:11.700
and this is my daughter holding a
plate [non-English word spoken].

00:34:11.700 --> 00:34:13.160
It's sprouted wheat.

00:34:13.160 --> 00:34:16.510
They symbolize abundance
and fertility,

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:19.630
and this is Baku-style baklava,
one of many styles of baklava

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:21.510
that is made in Azerbaijan.

00:34:21.510 --> 00:34:23.040
You can see the different styles,

00:34:23.040 --> 00:34:25.590
you can read about the different
types of baklava in my cookbook.

00:34:25.590 --> 00:34:30.130
This is a Baku style or Ganga style
baklava, and this is shakerbura.

00:34:30.130 --> 00:34:31.730
It's intricately designed
with something

00:34:31.730 --> 00:34:33.220
that is called [non-English
word spoken],

00:34:33.220 --> 00:34:37.280
and baklava actually
symbolizes stars.

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:41.550
Shakerbura symbolizes
half-moon, and this is shorgoghal.

00:34:41.550 --> 00:34:42.850
It symbolizes the sun.

00:34:42.850 --> 00:34:45.860
It's a flaky, spice-filled
flatbread.

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:47.210
They're really good.

00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:51.950
And the most important thing is
the tradition of hospitality.

00:34:51.950 --> 00:34:55.180
We have a saying that says,
"A house without a guest is

00:34:55.180 --> 00:34:56.480
like a mill without water."

00:34:56.480 --> 00:34:57.780
And it's very true.

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:01.140
For Westerners, our hospitality
may seem overwhelming,

00:35:01.140 --> 00:35:03.980
because we push everybody
to eat and drink.

00:35:03.980 --> 00:35:07.300
Even if you are not
hungry, you have to eat.

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:10.930
So you cannot refuse the food,
because you have to be polite,

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:13.960
because there is so much labor put
into preparing something for you.

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:16.240
Always express gratitude
to the host.

00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:20.730
At the very end, I wanted to
review this quote that I found

00:35:20.730 --> 00:35:24.030
in Alexander Dumas's book
Adventures in Caucasia.

00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:25.330
I really love this.

00:35:25.330 --> 00:35:28.030
It really gives the gist
Azerbaijani culture.

00:35:28.030 --> 00:35:29.730
So this is what he said.

00:35:29.730 --> 00:35:33.290
"The officer commanding the
nearby village of Sourakhani came

00:35:33.290 --> 00:35:36.020
to invite us to take tea with him.

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:37.940
Tea is hardly the right word,

00:35:37.940 --> 00:35:41.400
for we found he had prepared
an excellent supper for us,

00:35:41.400 --> 00:35:45.480
a Tatar meal of shashlyk,
pears, grapes, and watermelons.

00:35:45.480 --> 00:35:48.690
He also offered us rooms if
we cared to stay the night."

00:35:48.690 --> 00:35:52.020
Tatar, by the way, is how we were
called during the Russian Empire,

00:35:52.020 --> 00:36:00.150
and I hope you get to try the
signs of hospitality firsthand

00:36:00.150 --> 00:36:04.420
if you visit Azerbaijan, and I hope
you try the food of Azerbaijan.

